g.title: Folded Corner.69

g.text: Decorator pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle. Client code does not require change in case a Decorator is used instead of a Component. This is because the Decorator complies to the same interface. The client can use the Component and Decorator uniformly. Not only the client code can remain ‘unchanged’ but also the Component itself. We are adding extra responsibilities to the Component without changing existing code.

g.text: The Decorator pattern enables the possibility to extend the behavior of a single object and not the entire class. This can be useful when we don’t want to ‘impact’ all the instances with a new feature.

g.title: Folded Corner.129
g.desc: The Decorator pattern provides a lot of flexibility (attachin...

g.text: The Decorator pattern provides a lot of flexibility (attaching/detaching behavior to an object). However, this flexibility comes with a price. A lot of small, cohesive Decorators can results in a scattered code base that becomes hard to navigate and comprehend.

g.title: Folded Corner.133
g.desc: The Decorator pattern compliments Open Closed. However, using...

g.text: The Decorator pattern compliments Open Closed. However, using a Decorator extensively to comply to ‘extending without modification’, will result in wrappers around wrappers. These wrappers form a huge form of indirection, which negatively impacts navigability, debuggability and comprehending the code.

g.title: Folded Corner.138
g.desc: The Decorator pattern wraps an existing object and can extend...

g.text: The Decorator pattern wraps an existing object and can extend or exclude the behavior of the wrapped object. Excluding means the function call will result in an empty call or ‘dummy’ return. Extending means we add additional pre or post functionality on top of the existing functionality. The Decorator pattern makes it possible to change object behavior at runtime Instead of compile time (via static inheritance).

g.title: Folded Corner.176
g.desc: The Decorator pattern provides possibility to exclude behavio...

g.text: The Decorator pattern provides possibility to exclude behavior of an object. This might result in a violation of the Interface Segregation principle, because exclusion could result in empty function calls. Empty function calls result in redundant maintenance, because re-compilation and change will be required for these ‘un-interested’ functions.

g.title: Folded Corner.183
g.desc: The Decorator pattern could result easily in a violation of L...

g.text: The Decorator pattern could result easily in a violation of LSP. The post-conditions and/or the pre-conditions are modified by applying the decorator. This could result in strengthened pre-conditions and weakened post-conditions and thus a violation of Liskov Substitution.

g.title: Folded Corner.186
g.desc: The decorator pattern compliments the Single Responsibility p...

g.text: The decorator pattern compliments the Single Responsibility principle by separating responsibilities (e.g. logging or error-handling mechanisms) from the original object to provide readability, maintainability, testability and reusability across the code base. Readability, because ‘additional‘ logic is separated from ‘core’ logic, that would otherwise distract from the essence of the code. Maintainability, because the chances are smaller that we break something in a responsibility unrelated to the change. Reusability, because other Components can re-use the same decorator, but a Decorator can also re-use another Decorator (this is one of the reasons why the Decorator complies to the same interface as the Component). Testability, because we can test our decorator in isolation from the wrappee, which is not possible with static inheritance nor if we would combine Decorator logic into the ‘core’ logic.

g.title: Folded Corner.189
g.desc: The Decorator pattern can serve as an alternative to sub-clas...

g.text: The Decorator pattern can serve as an alternative to sub-classing. When sub-classing reaches exponential growth, it is often an indication that the issue should be resolved on the object level and not on the static class level. The Decorator resolves this class ‘explosion’ by applying composition and extracting responsibilities in a separate branch of the same class hierarchy. These individual responsibilities can be re-used amongst different Components and simplifies combinations. Another Use case for the Decorator pattern is when it is not possible to extend via sub-classing nor change, e.g. when the class is marked as ‘final’, sources are not available or we would break existing code.

g.title: Folded Corner.196
g.desc: It might be that a Decorator only ‘decorates’ a single functi...

g.text: It might be that a Decorator only ‘decorates’ a single function from the Component. This will result in ‘simple’ message forwarding for the rest of the Decorator. This can be labor intensive work. However, the abstract Decorator resolves this issue, because we implement it there and inherit from it in our concrete decorators.
